4.2 Maintenance Operations
==========================

 -- Pure Function: reduce::verbosity n

     Sets the verbosity level; 0 means no messages at all (which is the
     default when using this module), and the following values may be
     or’ed together to pick what you need:

          1: messages whenever garbage collection happens

          2: messages whenever a module of code is loaded

          4: extra details in the garbage collector messages

 -- Pure Function: reduce::switch name:string val::int

     Lets you change global Reduce options.  This works like Reduce’s
     ‘on’ and ‘off’ declarations; please check the Reduce documentation
     for details.

 -- Pure Function: reduce::capture flag::int
 -- Pure Function: reduce::output

     Captures output from Reduce.  If ‘flag’ is nonzero, *note
     reduce;;capture: e. arranges for all output from Reduce to be
     buffered.  The contents of the buffer can then be read using the
     *note reduce;;output: f. function which returns a string value.  If
     ‘flag’ is zero, capturing is disabled so that output goes to stdout
     again.

 -- Pure Function: reduce::feed s::string

     Feeds input to Reduce.  Reduce will read input from the given
     string ‘s’, switching back to stdin after ‘s’ has been processed.

 -- Pure Function: reduce::load name::string

     Loads Reduce packages.  This works like Reduce’s ‘load_package’
     command; please check the Reduce documentation for details.

 -- Pure Function: reduce::in name::string

     Sources the given Reduce (.red) file.  This works like the Lisp
     ‘in’ function.  Output is captured using *note reduce;;capture: e,
     see above.


