6.25 Plotting
=============

REDUCE can do 2- and 3-dimensional function plots through its gnuplot(1)
package.  Some examples (note that we have to quote the ‘x..y’ ranges
here so that they get through to Reduce, rather than being evaluated on
the Pure side):

     > simplify $ plot (sin x/x) (x=='(-15..15));

     // Multiple ranges.
     > simplify $ plot (sin(x^2 + y^2) / sqrt(x^2 + y^2)) [x=='(-12..12), y=='(-12..12)];

     // Specifying options.
     > simplify $ plot (cos (sqrt(x^2 + y^2))) [x=='(-3..3),y=='(-3 .. 3)] hidden3d;

     // Specifying points.
     > simplify $ plot [[0,0],[0,1],[1,1],[0,0],[1,0],[0,1],[0.5,1.5],[1,1],[1,0]];

     // Output options.
     > simplify $ plot (sin x) [x=='(0..10),terminal==postscript,output=="sin.ps"];


